Wiedemann, 1820
</taxonomicName>
, by subsequent designation (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA139D5FFCEDB72B1F047B299BA908C" author="Coquillett, D. W." box="[996,1218,707,731]" pageId="1" pageNumber="578" pagination="499 - 647" refId="ref9603" refString="Coquillett, D. W. (1910) The type-species of the North American genera of Diptera. Proceedings of the United States National Museum, 37, 499 - 647. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 00963801.37 - 1719.499" type="journal article" year="1910">Coquillett, 1910: 603</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8F4424FFCEDB72B283467899349677" blockId="1.[151,1437,777,1056]" pageId="1" pageNumber="578">
The species of the genus 
<taxonomicName id="4C303FA7FFCEDB72B3A6467B9FCF9174" authority="Loew, 1847" authorityName="Loew" authorityYear="1847" box="[434,695,777,804]" class="Insecta" family="Asilidae" genus="Saropogon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="578" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B9449836FFCEDB72B3A6467B9F549173" box="[434,556,778,804]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="578">Saropogon</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFA139D5FFCEDB72B027467B9FCF9174" author="Loew, H." box="[563,695,777,804]" pageId="1" pageNumber="578" pagination="384 - 568" refId="ref10493" refString="Loew, H. (1847) Uber die europaischen Raubfliegen (Diptera, Asilica). Linnaea Entomologica, 2, 384 - 568. [in German] https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 11475" type="journal article" year="1847">Loew, 1847</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
are medium sized flies with the marginal cell and all of the posterior cells widely open; the anal cell is widely open or narrowly closed. The head and abdomen droop and the head, in anterior view, is noticeably broader than high. The face is usually plane and without setae, except on the lower third or less and the setae are often confined to the epistomal margin. The protibial process is short and its spine is often twisted. The antennae are approximately as long as the head in lateral view. Acrostichal macrosetae on the mesonotum are differentiated. Femora with macrosetae greatly reduced or nearly absent. The abdomen is cylindroid, at most slightly tapered. The general coloration is often pale, sometimes black. The species of this genus tend to be variable and the sexes are often sexually dimorphic in color (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA139D5FFCEDB72B15641749EC79648" author="Back, E. A." box="[834,959,1029,1055]" pageId="1" pageNumber="578" pagination="137 - 400" refId="ref9549" refString="Back, E. A. (1909) The robber flies of America, north of Mexico, belonging to the subfamilies Leptogastrinae and Dasypogoninae. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 35, 137 - 400. https: // doi. org / 10.5962 / bhl. title. 9381" type="journal article" year="1909">Back 1909</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation id="EFA139D5FFCEDB72B1DF417499389677" author="Hull, F. M." box="[971,1088,1029,1056]" pageId="1" pageNumber="578" pagination="431 - 906" refId="ref10206" refString="Hull, F. M. (1962) Robber Flies of the World: The Genera of the Family Asilidae. In: Smithsonian Institution, United States National Museum. Bulletin 224. Part 2. Smithsonian Institution, United States National Museum, Washington, D. C., pp. 431 - 906. https: // doi. org / 10.5479 / si. 03629236.224" type="book chapter" year="1962">Hull 1962</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
